	(289,7,'2014-07-09 20:36:11','2014-07-09 20:36:11','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-315\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/1004805681-e1405100092880.jpg\" alt=\"test 1\" width=\"800\" height=\"1064\" /></p>\r\n<p>From buying new shoes, to connecting with high school buddies, to checking 401(k) account levels - and everything in between - were getting used to doing everything online. However, we dont always think twice when sharing information about ourselves with third parties, and this may put us at risk. In fact, in 2012, one American fell victim to identity theft every three seconds, and 85 percent of those incidents involved the fraudulent use of information linked to credit cards or bank accounts. <sup>1,2</sup></p>\r\n<p>It can be overwhelming to keep track of  let alone defend against  every digital danger we are exposed to. MetLife Defender makes it simple to safeguard against these threats, but following some simple tips can help keep your digital life intact.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>KEEP IT ON A NEED-TO-KNOW BASIS</strong>: Just because theres a box for it, doesnt mean you have to fill it out. When shopping online, provide the minimum amount of information necessary to complete your order and be wary of questions that seem unrelated to your purchase.<sup>3</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>SWITCH IT UP</strong>: The password for your bank account should always be different than the password you use for websites where you shop or watch videos. Having multiple passwords can help decrease the chances of others accessing your online accounts.<sup>4</sup>MetLife Defender can help protect your online account logins, so be sure to keep them updated on your Member Dashboard.</li>\r\n<li><strong>DONT LEAVE A TRACE</strong>: When you no longer need them, shred credit card offers or applications, insurance forms, physician billing statements, voided or deposited checks, and similar sources of personal data.<sup>5</sup> Also, make sure to clear your phone and computer of all personal information before disposing of them, in case they fall into the wrong hands.<sup>5</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>BE A LITTLE MYSTERIOUS</strong>: Keep your personal information private by making sure you never post sensitive items like your Social Security number, date of birth, address, phone number, or account numbers on social media or other publicly-accessible sites.<sup>5</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>DONT BE AFRAID TO DELETE</strong>: If an email or social media post seems suspicious, delete it or mark it as spam. Do not click on unfamiliar links that could compromise your computer.<sup>5</sup></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Peace of mind is only a click away. <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll in MetLife Defender</a> today!</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Pascual, Alphonse and Sarah Miller. (2013, February). 2013 Identity Fraud Report. Javelin Strategy.Retrieved from https://www.javelinstrategy.com/news/1387/92/1<br />2. Harrell, Erika and Lynn Langton. (2013, December 12). <em>Victims of Identity Theft, 2012.</em> Bureau of Justice Statistics. Retrieved from http://www.bjs.gov/index.cfm?ty=pbdetail&amp;iid=4821<br />3. Identity Theft Resource Center.<em> ITRC Fact Sheet 103 Online Shopping. </em>. Retrieved from http://www.idtheftcenter.org/index.php/Fact-Sheets/fs-103.html<br />4. Microsoft.<em>Six rules for safer financial transactions online. </em>Retrieved from http://www.microsoft.com/security/online-privacy/finances-rules.aspx<br />5. Federal Trade Commission. (2012, July). <em>How to Keep Your Personal Information Secure.</em>http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0272-how-keep-your-personal-information-secure</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714383474[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Off the Record: 6 Tips to Protect Your Personal Information Online','','publish','open','open','