	(460,7,'2014-07-11 18:45:05','2014-07-11 18:45:05','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-472\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/15-Article-Medical-Identity-Theft-Inconvenient-Prevalent-and-Dangerous-Image-3000x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Paying For Healthcare With Credit Card\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\" /></p>\r\n<p>Many of us go to great lengths to protect ourselves online and offusing unique passwords, only visiting secure sites, and shredding important documents. But do you ever think twice about the safety of your medical information?</p>\r\n<p>Recent statistics gathered by the Identity Theft Resource Center show that 43 percent of all identity theft reported in 2013 was medical identity theft.<sup>1</sup> What does medical identity theft look like? The following highlights example threats to your medical information and introduces precautions you can take to ensure your information is safe.</p>\r\n<p><strong>The bill for surgery  that you didnt have!</strong></p>\r\n<p>Your first alert will generally appear in your health insurance Explanation of Benefits in the form of an unknown code. The code, representing a prescription for OxyContin or Viagra, will be there as a reminder of the surgery recovery unbeknownst to you. In either case, neither you nor anyone else in your family was the patient, meaning that someone else received medical services under your name. Aside from the financial burden, this also means you may not be eligible for that same surgery should you actually need it. </p>\r\n<p><strong>The prescription thats already been refilled</strong></p>\r\n<p>On your trip to the pharmacy to refill your monthly prescription, you find that its already been picked up. You meander home expecting another family member to have stopped by the pharmacy, except neither you nor your family did so. What happened to your prescription? And who could have picked it up? Unfortunately someone else might be using your meds or benefitting from reselling them.</p>\r\n<p><strong>The faulty info</strong></p>\r\n<p>Imagine that youre getting pre-screened before a scheduled surgery. However, as nurses verify key information with you, you realize the file is all wrongfrom blood type to medical history. This is a scenario where someone else could have had access to your files and changed the data to reflect their own personal information. Although it may only be troublesome in this case, it could be fatal if you needed urgent treatment.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Give your medical information a check up</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Ask!</strong> Your doctors office requires a lot of personal information, from insurance information, to your phone number, to your Social Securitynumber, family names, birthdays, and even credit card information. Make sure you ask how they store the data and what information is consistently kept on file. Research shows that medical office employees are often allowed to access information from personal devices that may not be protected against hacking.<sup>2</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>Dig deep</strong>. While your benefit statements from your insurance company can be complicated, dont just set them aside. Read what youre being billed for, including the physician and date of service. This way, you can catch a problem early on and take the appropriate action to remedy the situation.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Protect</strong>. Give medical insurance cards and flexible spending account credit cards to appropriate personnel only and keep them safely tucked away when not in use.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Increase your dose of security</strong></p>\r\n<p>There is a substantial amount of personal and medical information that you need to keep track of and it can oftentimes be overwhelming; to assist you in protecting your data, enroll in MetLife Defendera comprehensive and proactive approach to managing and securing your and your familys health information. MetLife Defender gives you an enhanced layer of protection against medical identity theft and medical fraud through specialized services designed to specifically protect your personal health information.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/?gclid=CjwKEAjw9LKeBRDurOugs43jnlgSJACUXqHx78H5vVXI0Me7QgxKj5yz_7R06jbnbCsR3lp4d4-EDhoCqjfw_wcB\">Visit MetLife Defender</a> and see how you can enroll today!</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Ollove, Michael. (2014, February 7). <em>The Rise of Medical Identity Theft in Healthcare</em>. Kaiser Health News.Retrieved from: http://www.kaiserhealthnews.org/stories/2014/february/07/rise-of-indentity-theft.asp</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">2. Levin, Adam. (2014, March 17). <em>Medical Identity Theft: Does the Health Care Industry Think It\'s Too Big for Its Breaches?</em>. The Ponemon Institute. Retrieved from http://www.ponemon.org/blog/fourth-annual-benchmark-study-on-patient-privacy-and-data-security</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div id=\"imcontent\" dir=\"ltr\"><span dir=\"ltr\" style=\"color: #000000; font-size: 8pt;\">L0614380272[exp0615][All States][DC]</span></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Medical Identity Theft: Inconvenient, Prevalent and Dangerous','','publish','open','open','','460','','','2014-08-13 22:48:34','2014-08-13 22:48:34','',0,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/?p=460',0,'post','',0),
	(466,7,'2014-07-11 18:51:34','2014-07-11 18:51:34','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-469\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/14-Article-Good-Habits-Mean-Safety-Long-Term-3000x2000.jpg\" alt=\"14 - Article - Good Habits Mean Safety Long Term\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><em>Tips for Protecting Our Tech-Savvy Kids from Online Identity Theft</em></span></p>\r\n<p>LOL. OMG. TTYS. If you have kids, you probably know what were talking about. And while this innocent cyber language can be fun, its also a clue to how much time our children are spending online and the risks involved with it.</p>\r\n<p>A 2013 poll showed that the average tween and teen spent at least five hours per day online, and 86percentof them believed social networking sites to be safe.<sup>1</sup> Almost all of their parents agreed, but unfortunately, this is not the case.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Easy as A.B.C.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Predators and cybercriminals are going after an easier target these days: our children. Between cell phones, tablets, and laptops, todays children are rarely more than a click away from the digital worldeven while at school. And stealing a childs information is easier than you think.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Who are they talking to?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Our children have the world at their fingertips. That also means that they can communicate with a world full of people. And while they may be gaming, chatting, and sharing with friends, they could also be interacting with complete strangers.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Passwords are only as strong as you make them</strong></p>\r\n<p>We often create passwords that have to do with our personal life, referencing information such as our address, phone number and birth date. Unfortunately, our kids do this too and the abundance of information on the Internet makes it incredibly simple for someone to steal.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Does it really matter? And how much can they find out about my child online?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Absolutely! Aside from your childs safety, his or her identity is also at risk. And for that matter, your identity. Imagine finding out that your daughter has a mortgage (unpaid of course) in a faraway state, or that your son has outstanding hospital bills. It seems impossible, but because we typically dont keep close tabs on what kind of information our children are sharing, identity theft happens. And its no laughing matter. Child identity theft can cause huge problems for them down the road when they want to buy a car or apply for student loans.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Protect yourself and your children from online danger</strong></p>\r\n<p>MetLife Defendercan help by providing constant monitoring, protection, and resources to keep you safe. <strong><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll today</a> and start experiencing better online protection for you and your family.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. McAfee. (2013, June). <em>McAfee Digital Deception Study 2013. </em>Retrieved from: http://www.mcafee.com/us/resources/reports/rp-digital-deception-survey.pdf</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0614379029[exp0615][All States][DC]</span></p>','Your Children: Good Habits Now Mean Safety Long-Term','','publish','open','open','','your-children-good-habits-now-mean-safety-long-term','','','2014-08-12 18:23:28','2014-08-12 18:23:28','',0,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/?p=466',0,'post','',0),
