	(661,7,'2014-07-14 15:09:14','2014-07-14 15:09:14','<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Bullying isnt a new phenomenon  it has existed for years. In fact, many of us can still remember the name of our own schoolyard bully.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">But modern technology and social media have spawned a new, more prevalent form of bullying known as cyberbullying. Like the instances you remember from the playground, cyberbullying can having lasting effects on todays children and parents alike. Education and an open dialogue within families can go a long way. Answer these questions to see how up-to-date you are on the topic of cyberbullying:</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">[playbuzz-game game=https://www.playbuzz.com/meganahearn10/cyberbullying-just-a-buzzword-or-a-legitimate-problem]</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">As a parent, its important to keep the lines of communication open and create a safe, non-judgmental environment where your child feels he or she can share issues as they come up. Its also important to keep tabs on the various platforms your children are using as 90percent of all bullying originates on the popular networking sites of Facebook, Twitter, and Instagram.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Through MetLife Defenders Anti Cyberbullying App, parents can receive real-time alerts when their child is a suspected victim of online threats or cyberbullying. Trusting MetLife Defender and utilizing the anti-cyberbullying features does not mean you are spying on your children; rather you are proactively protecting them against a wide range of online threats including cyberbullying, ID theft, and the appropriation of their financial and personal information.</span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\"><strong>Sign up for MetLife Defender</strong></a><strong> and take advantage of the easy-to-install app.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. Patchin, J. W. &amp; Hinduja, S. (2010). Cyberbullying and self-esteem. Journal of School Health, 80(12), 614-621. Retrieved from: http://www.cyberbullying.us/cyberbullying_and_self_esteem_research_fact_sheet.pdf</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">2. Cyber Bullying: Statistics and Tips. I-SAFE America Survey. Retrieved from: http://www.bullyingstatistics.org/content/bullying-statistics.html</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">3. Cyberbullying FAQ for Teens. National Crime Prevention Council. http://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/cyberbullying-faq-for-teens</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0614379031[exp0615][All States][DC]</span></p>','Cyberbullying: Just a Buzzword or a Legitimate Problem?','','publish','open','open','','cyberbullying-just-a-buzzword-or-a-legitimate-problem','','','2014-08-15 19:30:03','2014-08-15 19:30:03','',0,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/?p=661',0,'post','',0),
	(664,2,'2014-07-18 15:16:22','2014-07-18 15:16:22','<p>MetLife Defender is a 24/7, comprehensive solution that proactively monitors and protects you and your family against the full range of today\'s Internet threats. From identity theft and financial fraud to cyberbullying and beyond, MetLife Defender is always on guard for you.</p>','MetLife Defender, Always on Guard','','inherit','open','open','','487-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 15:16:22','2014-07-18 15:16:22','',487,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/487-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(665,2,'2014-07-18 15:16:39','2014-07-18 15:16:39','<p>In 2013, more than 2 million people were victims of medical identity fraud. The cost per each victim was about the same as the price of a compact SUV. MetLife Defender proactively monitors medical and health record data -- in addition to your bank accounts.</p>','Enjoy your digital life','','inherit','open','open','','493-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 15:16:39','2014-07-18 15:16:39','',493,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/493-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(666,2,'2014-07-18 15:17:20','2014-07-18 15:17:20','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-315\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/1004805681-e1405100092880.jpg\" alt=\"test 1\" width=\"800\" height=\"1064\" /></p>\r\n<p>From buying new shoes, to connecting with high school buddies, to checking 401(k) account levels - and everything in between - were getting used to doing everything online. However, we dont always think twice when sharing information about ourselves with third parties, and this may put us at risk. In fact, in 2012, one American fell victim to identity theft every three seconds, and 85 percent of those incidents involved the fraudulent use of information linked to credit cards or bank accounts. <sup>1,2</sup></p>\r\n<p>It can be overwhelming to keep track of  let alone defend against  every digital danger we are exposed to. MetLife Defender makes it simple to safeguard against these threats, but following some simple tips can help keep your digital life intact.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>KEEP IT ON A NEED-TO-KNOW BASIS</strong>:Just because theres a box for it, doesnt mean you have to fill it out. When shopping online, provide the minimum amount of information necessary to complete your order and be wary of questions that seem unrelated to your purchase.<sup>3</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>SWITCH IT UP</strong>: The password for your bank account should always be different than the password you use for websites where you shop or watch videos. Having multiple passwords can help decrease the chances of others accessing your online accounts.<sup>4</sup>MetLife Defender can help protect your online account logins, so be sure to keep them updated on your Member Dashboard.</li>\r\n<li><strong>DONT LEAVE A TRACE</strong>:When you no longer need them, shred credit card offers or applications, insurance forms, physician billing statements, voided or deposited checks, and similar sources of personal data.<sup>5</sup> Also, make sure to clear your phone and computer of all personal information before disposing of them, in case they fall into the wrong hands.<sup>5</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>BE A LITTLE MYSTERIOUS</strong>:Keep your personal information private by making sure you never post sensitive items like your Social Security Number, date of birth, address, phone number, or account numbers on social media or other publicly-accessible sites.<sup>5</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>DONT BE AFRAID TO DELETE</strong>: If an email or social media post seems suspicious, delete it or mark it as spam. Do not click on unfamiliar links that could compromise your computer.<sup>5</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>STAY ALERT</strong>: As a valued member, MetLife Defender works to protect you 24/7 and will send you real-time alerts if any suspicious activity is detected.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Peace of mind is only a click away. <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll</a> in MetLife Defender today!</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><strong></strong>Pascual, Alphonse and Sarah Miller. (2013, February). 2013 Identity Fraud Report. Javelin Strategy.Retrieved from <a href=\"https://www.javelinstrategy.com/news/1387/92/1\">https://www.javelinstrategy.com/news/1387/92/1</a></li>\r\n<li>Harrell, Erika and Lynn Langton. (2013, December 12). <em>Victims of Identity Theft, 2012.</em> Bureau of Justice Statistics. Retrieved from <a href=\"http://www.bjs.gov/index.cfm?ty=pbdetail&amp;iid=4821\">http://www.bjs.gov/index.cfm?ty=pbdetail&amp;iid=4821</a></li>\r\n<li>Identity Theft Resource Center.<em> ITRC Fact Sheet 103 Online Shopping. </em>. Retrieved from <a href=\"http://www.idtheftcenter.org/index.php/Fact-Sheets/fs-103.html\">http://www.idtheftcenter.org/index.php/Fact-Sheets/fs-103.html</a></li>\r\n<li>Microsoft.<em>Six rules for safer financial transactions online. </em>Retrieved from <a href=\"http://www.microsoft.com/security/online-privacy/finances-rules.aspx\">http://www.microsoft.com/security/online-privacy/finances-rules.aspx</a></li>\r\n<li>Federal Trade Commission. (2012, July). <em>How to Keep Your Personal Information Secure.</em><a href=\"http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0272-how-keep-your-personal-information-secure\">http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0272-how-keep-your-personal-information-secure</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>L0514375773[exp0515][All States][DC]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Off the Record: 6 Tips to Protect Your Personal Information Online','','inherit','open','open','','289-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 15:17:20','2014-07-18 15:17:20','',289,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/289-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(668,8,'2014-07-18 15:44:34','2014-07-18 15:44:34','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-417\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/1784001601-3000x2001.jpg\" alt=\"178400160\" width=\"800\" height=\"534\" /></p>\r\n<p>The busier we get, the more we turn to quick fixes like online shopping, online banking and social media to stay on top of our everyday lives. In 2013, Americans spent more than $262 billion online and approximately 51 percent of U.S. adults were banking online.<sup>1,2</sup>However, with online theft and fraud becoming more sophisticated, its important to take precautions to protect ourselves.</p>\r\n<p>Annually, more than 11.5 million Americans fall victim to identity theft, and studies indicate that an average of $4,930 is lost per incident.<sup>3</sup> MetLife Defender is always on guard to make sure you dont become one of these statistics. Keep the following tips in mind to help educate yourself on what you can do to keep your personal and financial information secure.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>DONT SHARE YOUR BIRTHDAY</strong>: If all of your Facebook friends can find it with one click, then your birthday probably isnt as secure as you think. To create a strong, unique password for your financial accounts, make sure you steer away from using easily accessible information like your birthday or family members names in your password.</li>\r\n<li><strong>PRACTICE SAFETY FIRST: </strong>If youre visiting a financial website, make sure you are using secure internet like your home service and not public Wi-Fi. </li>\r\n<li><strong>DONT FRET</strong>: You lost your wallet  weve all been there. Visit the Lost Wallet Protection [hyperlink to page] page so we can help you recover from the loss and continue safeguarding your information.</li>\r\n<li><strong>DONT <em>CLICK HERE</em>: </strong>If it seems suspicious, it probably is. To ensure every security alert you receive from your financial institution is authentic, check to see if it contains email links or ask you to call phone numbers. If so, cross-check this information with the contact information on your financial institutions website or visit the website directly to login.<sup>4</sup></li>\r\n<li><strong>PLAY DEFENSE:</strong> Is all of your financial information up-to-date on your MetLife Defender Member Dashboard? Take a minute and make sure, so MetLife Defender can proactively protect your financial data.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Need more help? <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll</a> in MetLife Defender today!</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Sehgal, Vikram and Jeff Wray. (2013, February 27). Online Retail Forecast, 2012 to 2017. Forrester Research. Retrieved from <a href=\"http://www.forrester.com/US+Online+Retail+Forecast+2009+To+2014/fulltext/-/E-RES56551\">http://www.forrester.com/US+Online+Retail+Forecast+2009+To+2014/fulltext/-/E-RES56551</a></li>\r\n<li>Fox, Susannah. (2013, August 7). 51% of U.S. Adults Bank Online. Pew Research. Retrieved from <a href=\"http://www.pewinternet.org/2013/08/07/51-of-u-s-adults-bank-online/\">http://www.pewinternet.org/2013/08/07/51-of-u-s-adults-bank-online/</a></li>\r\n<li>U.S. Department of Justice, Javelin Strategy &amp; Research.(2013, June 18). Identity Theft/Fraud Statistics.</li>\r\n<li>Federal Trade Commission. (2011, September).<em>Consumer Information: Phishing.</em> Retrieved from <a href=\"http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0003-phishing\">http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0003-phishing</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p> L0514375768[exp0515][All States][DC]</p>','Keep Cybercriminals at Bay: 5 Tips to Protect Your Financial Data and Identity','','inherit','open','open','','416-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 15:44:34','2014-07-18 15:44:34','',416,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/416-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(669,8,'2014-07-18 15:45:04','2014-07-18 15:45:04','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-485\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/WhereIsMyData_Infographic_hires_060311.jpg\" alt=\"DM132_D5535_WhereIsMyData_Infographic 2\" width=\"800\" height=\"674\" /><em>Where did I put my keys? Where on earth did my cellphone go? Did I leave my purse in the car?</em></p>\r\n<p>You ask yourself these questions every day, but do you ever wonder, <em>Where is my data? </em>If not, its a question you should start asking! Having this knowledge allows you to keep better track of your personal information.</p>\r\n<p>We cant help ourselves. Its become commonplace to depend on apps, websites and a slew of online resources to buy items, review bank account information and send emails every day. Anytime you enter your email address, connect on Facebook, or make an online purchase with your credit card, you are transmitting personally identifiable information that could end up in the wrong hands.</p>\r\n<p>And sometimes, it does.</p>\r\n<p>The vast majority of identity theft incidentsabout 85 percentinvolve the fraudulent use of accessible account information. An average of 12 million Americans fall victim to identity fraud annually.<sup>1</sup> And in 2013, financial losses totaling $21 billion were attributed to cybercrime.<sup>2</sup></p>\r\n<p>If your data is lost or stolen, the effects can be stressful and devastating. MetLife Defender is a proactive, comprehensive solution that will protect your data and help you avoid these risks.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll</a> in MetLife Defender today so we can monitor your information and keep you safe online.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Bureau of Justice Statistics.<a href=\"http://www.bjs.gov/index.cfm?ty=pbdetail&amp;iid=4821\"><strong>http://www.bjs.gov/index.cfm?ty=pbdetail&amp;iid=4821</strong></a>. Retrieved February 2014.</li>\r\n<li>Javelin Strategy &amp; Research.<em>2013 Identity Theft Fraud Statistics from Statistic Brain, U.S. Department of Justice</em>, 2013.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>L0514375772[exp0515][All States][DC]</p>','Where is Your Data?','','inherit','open','open','','419-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 15:45:04','2014-07-18 15:45:04','',419,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/419-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(671,8,'2014-07-18 15:48:03','2014-07-18 15:48:03','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-475\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/12-Article-Are-You-Password-Savvy-Image-3000x2297.jpg\" alt=\"12 - Article - Are You Password Savvy Image\" width=\"800\" height=\"613\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Test your smarts!</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>If youre not an identity thief, it can be hard to think like one! Take this quick quiz to see if you can outsmart a cyber criminal.</p>\r\n<p><strong>True or False</strong>:</p>\r\n<p>You run a decorating business from home and like to use your business name as a password, making it complex by adding a number, the year you started it: spaceliftchicago95. This is a very secure password.</p>\r\n<p><strong>False!</strong> <em>This could be an easy guess for criminals! Think about all of the places your information is displayed on the Web  from LinkedIn to the online white pages not to mention in print format. Anyone with your name can find that you own a business  and the year you started!</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Which of the following is a great password?</strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Cindyjohnellory (your three kids)</li>\r\n<li>Cindyjohnellory35 (your three kids  plus your address number!)</li>\r\n<li>CindyJohnEllory35 (same as above  but with caps)</li>\r\n<li>None of the above!</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>4. Youre right  none of the above is the correct choice because caps or no caps, and numbers aside, your childrens names are just too easy for a cybercriminal to guess. A simple google search or a Facebook photo can lead right to your childrens name. TIP: If you really want to use their names as a base, make it strong by taking out the second letter of each and incorporate a randomized number into the password</em>: <strong>Cndy6Jhn2Elory. </strong><em>Now thats a stumper!</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Your daughter is selecting a security term for her first credit card. You advise her to:</strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Go with your maiden name; after all, that cant be tied to her.</li>\r\n<li>Use your pets name; who would ever guess Mr. Fuzzles?</li>\r\n<li>Pick a recent vacation spot  it was really fun!</li>\r\n<li>Use a random combination of numbers and letters.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Number four is the way to go! True that it can be challenging to remember random passwords, but numbers 1  3 are not safe! Your maiden name? Easily accessed through a connection on social media or an alumni database. The pet? Youve posted the pictures online</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>If you got all three correct  good for you!</strong> Youre well on the way to foiling a cyber criminal.</p>\r\n<p><strong>If you got fewer than three right, dont be alarmed.</strong> But do take a hard look at your passwords and make some changes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Check out more resources on strong passwords and online safety in the Tools &amp; Tips section of MetLifeDefender.com and sign up for a free trial!</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Are You Password Savvy?','','inherit','open','open','','453-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 15:48:03','2014-07-18 15:48:03','',453,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/453-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(673,8,'2014-07-18 15:48:42','2014-07-18 15:48:42','<p>In 2013, more than 2 million people were victims of medical identity fraud. The cost per each victim was about the same as the price of a compact SUV. MetLife Defender proactively monitors medical and health record data -- in addition to your bank accounts.</p>','Enjoy Your Digital Life','','inherit','open','open','','493-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 15:48:42','2014-07-18 15:48:42','',493,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/493-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(674,8,'2014-07-18 15:49:09','2014-07-18 15:49:09','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-445\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/42-220991701-3000x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Woman Holding Credit Card\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\" /></p>\r\n<p>Protecting yourself at home and on the run.</p>\r\n<p>Weve all been using the Web long enough to know the basics of Internet protectionfrom creating strong passwords to deleting suspicious emails. But often we set those rules aside for the convenience of having the Internet at our fingertips.</p>\r\n<p>Meeting friends at the coffee shop, you may also check email via their unsecured server. Waiting for your daughter at ballet, you might also catch up on banking through their public Wi-Fi. However, unsecured networks are especially tempting to thieves looking for access to your data. So as you walk away with your coffee and balanced checkbook, they can also walk away with your personal information.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Sharing, sharing, everywhere</strong></p>\r\n<p>Your sensitive personal information may be in places youre unaware of. Whether you visited the doctor with a sick child or your accountant during tax season, your information could be susceptible with these unsuspecting yet trustworthy companies. For example, if the data entry clerk at your doctors office is downloading and listening to music while inputting information, the clerk is opening up a P2P network vulnerable to a security breach.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Cyber crime is increasing</strong></p>\r\n<p>Perhaps youve heard about a friend of a friend who had their data stolen by making a routine purchase at the local grocery store. While you may shrug this off as an unlikely occurrence, its actually more common than you think. In fact, 13.1 million consumers suffered identity fraud in 2013.<sup>1</sup> Thieves have developed ways to use software remotely to extract credit and debit card data from inside a store. This means your trip to pick up milk and bread could be a dangerous one.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Protect yourself and your information</strong></p>\r\n<p>In the end, we all love the convenience that our smart devices and the Web offer. However, we need to be smarter than those devices in order to keep our information safe. Thats why MetLife Defender is here. MetLife Defender provides comprehensive protection against the full range of online threats with round-the-clock security to stop these threats before they occur.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>If youd like to have the peace of mind 24/7 security provides, <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">enroll</a> with MetLife Defender today.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Sehgal, Vikram and Jeff Wray. (2013, February 27). <em>Online Retail Forecast, 2012 to 2017</em>. Forrester Research.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>L0614379036[exp0615][All States][DC]</p>','A Latteand a Little Data, To Go','','inherit','open','open','','443-revision-v1','','','2014-07-18 15:49:09','2014-07-18 15:49:09','',443,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/443-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
