	(923,8,'2014-07-28 19:58:10','2014-07-28 19:58:10','<p><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-920\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/20-Article-Online-Child-Predation-7-8-14-Image-2000x3000.jpg\" alt=\"imsis550-173\" width=\"2000\" height=\"3000\" /><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; font-style: italic;\">Tips for Keeping Your Children Safe Online</span></p>\r\n<p>Never accept a ride from a stranger. Come straight home from school. Dont talk to strangers.</p>\r\n<p>If youre like most parents, youve been having similar conversations with your children since they were old enough to talk. But today, the danger doesnt just look like a suspicious character in a strange car, it exists online. Todays technology makes it easier than ever for strangers to target and contact your children. Get up to speed on the dangers they face and talk to your children about being safe online.</p>\r\n<p><strong>The online stranger</strong></p>\r\n<p>Its simple. Stranger equals no. Its easy for anyone to message your son or daughter about his or her favorite sports team, or even pretend to be a mutual friend of relatives. Remind your child if he or she is contacted by a stranger not to respond to the person in question and tell an adult.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Privacy please!</strong></p>\r\n<p>Privacy nowadays is more than shutting your door or closing the blinds, online privacy is key too! Read the privacy settings on all social media sites and decide with your child exactly how much information is best to share. Educate your child about what could happen if sensitive information is made available to strangers.</p>\r\n<p><strong>A friend of a friends friend doesnt have to be a friend of yours</strong></p>\r\n<p>Online sites are great at suggesting people you might know. Children and teens enjoy having large social networks, which makes it intriguing to accept friend requests from people who are friends with their social groups. It is important to review that just because an individual is a friend or relative of a friend, does not mean it is safe. While it can be fun for your child to connect the dots back from the friend she met at the beach last summer to your second cousins tennis instructors daughter, its an activity best done by you and your child together.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Taking control</strong></p>\r\n<p>Keeping tabs on your childs digital life can be overwhelming, even if you are armed with the best tips. MetLife Defenders Family Plan is a great option to monitor your childs social media accounts when you cant. It consistently scans your childs Facebook, Twitter and Instagram accounts to flag any suspected acts of predation and cyberbullying. <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\"><strong>Learn more about your options here.</strong></a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384029[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','A Lot More Than Child\'s Play','','publish','open','open','','923','','','2014-08-13 22:46:31','2014-08-13 22:46:31','',0,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/?p=923',0,'post','',0),
