	(931,8,'2014-07-28 21:14:53','2014-07-28 21:14:53','<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-933\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/21-Article-Oversharing-Online-Image-3000x1999.jpg\" alt=\"21 - Article - Oversharing Online Image\" width=\"3000\" height=\"1999\" /><em>How Much is Too Much?</em></span></p>\r\n<p>Its so much easier for our children to connect with friends today. New or old, they are just a click away. With each post, like, check-in or status update, they share a little bit about themselves and their families. Before this bad habit becomes a risk to your entire family, talk to your children about smart and safe behavior online.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Forever is a long time</strong></p>\r\n<p>Its fun to be the first to post a crazy photo from a great weekend or a silly video of friends. But before each post, encourage your child to think about the implications. Sometimes these posts can garner unwanted attention. By the time you try to delete them, it may be too late and the damage can linger for years to come.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Personal means personal</strong></p>\r\n<p>About half of teens report that they have shared their email addresses online, about one-third has shared phone numbers, and 15 percent say theyve published a home address.<sup>1</sup></p>\r\n<p>If this information ends up in the wrong hands, it could be dangerous. Strangers with access to your home address could commit mail fraud, stage a break-in or even use the information to steal your identity. Children may not see the bigger picture, so talk to them about the risks associated with sharing personal information.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Privacy is key</strong></p>\r\n<p>Despite what some may think, what happens on one device doesnt necessarily stay on that device and could end up on the Internet. Sit down with your children and talk about keeping personal photos personal and not to share via text or social media. Its important for children to understand that just because they are practicing safe Internet practices, others may not be and could share photos that you dont want seen by the public. </p>\r\n<p><strong>Real-time alerts</strong></p>\r\n<p>Empower your kids and teens to ask questions about what to share online and to talk to you about any issues with their online life. MetLife Defender is here to help you stay educated on issues affecting your kids online.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/online-child-safety/923/\">Learn more about safe Internet practices</a> and options for enrolling in our Family Plan to get alerts on suspected acts of cyberbullying or predation on your childrens Facebook, Twitter or Instagram accounts.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><sup>1</sup>McAfee. (July, 2014) <em>McAfees 2014 Teens and Screens</em>. Retrieved from http://blogs.mcafee.com/consumer/teens-and-screens</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384026[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Oversharing Online: TMI!','','publish','open','open','','tmi','','','2014-08-13 22:44:08','2014-08-13 22:44:08','',0,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/?p=931',0,'post','',0),
