	(977,7,'2014-08-12 17:49:10','2014-08-12 17:49:10','<p><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-832\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/23-Article-Password-Dos-and-Donts-Image-3000x2002.jpg\" alt=\"23 - Article - Password Dos and Donts Image\" width=\"3000\" height=\"2002\" />We all know that keeping complex passwords can help keep cybercriminals away from our sensitive information online. But are we taking this advice seriously? The latest findings may surprise you!</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>The most common password in 2013? 123456!</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>Thats according to SplashData  a password management company that compiles an annual report of users most common passwords, gathered by data posted by hackers.<sup>1</sup></p>\r\n<p>The other top passwords for 2013 included password, abc123 and 111111.</p>\r\n<p>While these passwords are easy to draft and remember, they are also easy to guess. Here are some tips for creating strong passwords:</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Password DONTs:</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>While it may seem obvious to some, it clearly isnt to the majority:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Dont use a string of consecutive numbers or letters, especially starting with 1 or a</li>\r\n<li>Dont include the name of the application (i.e., adobe123)</li>\r\n<li>Dont use your name, address or company information</li>\r\n<li>Dont save your passwords within a document on your computer</li>\r\n<li>If the word seems like something your kindergartener could guess  keep thinking!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong><em>Password DOs:</em></strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Do vary it up, using a different password for each online account</li>\r\n<li>Do get complicated, with randomized numbers to make things complicated for cybercriminals</li>\r\n<li>Do change your passwords every few months</li>\r\n<li>Do stay off the list. If its on the list of common passwords above, dont use it for your password!</li>\r\n<li>Capital letters, symbols, underscores, oh my! Adding in these extra elements can help make any password complex</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Get smart about online safety. <strong>Understand your risks and <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?src=carousel\">enroll in a free trial of MetLife Defender</a> to get comprehensive protection for your personal data online.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><sup>1</sup> Splash Data. (2014) <em>Worst Password List.</em> Retrieved from: http://splashdata.com/press/worstpasswords2013.htm</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384030[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Password Dos and Don\'ts','','inherit','open','open','','828-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 17:49:10','2014-08-12 17:49:10','',828,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/828-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(978,7,'2014-08-12 17:49:54','2014-08-12 17:49:54','<p><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-941\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/22-Article-Heartbleed-Image-3000x2250.jpg\" alt=\"22 - Article - Heartbleed Image\" width=\"3000\" height=\"2250\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><em>Protecting Your Privacy on the Web</em></span></p>\r\n<p>Eavesdropping on conversations. Stealing data. Impersonating users. The elements of a great spy novel?</p>\r\n<p>Sure, but in this case, theyre the results of the recent Heartbleed bug which served as an important wake up call for safer Internet behaviors.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Bug in brief</strong></p>\r\n<p>The infamous 2014 Heartbleed bug took the Internet by storm and potentially exposed millions of usernames and passwords on several of todays most popular sites.</p>\r\n<p>Unlike large scale data breaches of the past few years, the Heartbleed bug was a new type of breach which affected a code known as OpenSSL. OpenSSL is widely used across websites to encrypt user-provided information on servers and it is estimated that nearly two-thirds of all Internet sites use the code.</p>\r\n<p><strong>So what?</strong></p>\r\n<p>While all this technical Internet talk may leave you scratching your head, what you really need to know is that your information could still be at risk. A new report shows that as many as 300,000 sites are still vulnerable with many failing to implement the patches now that the initial scare is over.<sup>1 </sup></p>\r\n<p>MetLife Defenders security analysts suggest changing and varying your passwords on the following websites that may have been affected, if you havent already done so:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>DropBox</li>\r\n<li>Facebook</li>\r\n<li>Flickr</li>\r\n<li>Google</li>\r\n<li>Gmail</li>\r\n<li>Instagram</li>\r\n<li>OkCupid</li>\r\n<li>Tumblr</li>\r\n<li>Yahoo</li>\r\n<li>Yahoo Mail</li>\r\n<li>YouTube</li>\r\n<li>Wikipedia</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>While this does not mean that your information was exposed, it\'s always better to be safe than sorry and avoid incidents of identity theft.</p>\r\n<p>If you are worried that your data is vulnerable, <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\"><strong>enroll in MetLife Defender</strong></a> to get proactive protection for your financial, medical and personal data online.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><sup>1</sup> Erratta Security (2014) Retrieved from: http://blog.erratasec.com/2014/05/300k-servers-vulnerable-to-heartbleed.html#.U7RxypRdXHW</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714383411[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Stop the Heartbleeding','','inherit','open','open','','939-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 17:49:54','2014-08-12 17:49:54','',939,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/939-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(979,7,'2014-08-12 18:02:16','2014-08-12 18:02:16','<p>[soliloquy id=\"899\"]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. National Crime Prevention Council. <i>Cyberbullying: Spotting the Signs</i>. Retrieved from: <a href=\"http://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/cyberbullying-tip-sheets/NCPC%20Tip%20Sheet%20-%20Spotting%20The%20Signs.pdf\">http</a><a href=\"http://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/cyberbullying-tip-sheets/NCPC%20Tip%20Sheet%20-%20Spotting%20The%20Signs.pdf\">://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/cyberbullying-tip-sheets/NCPC%20Tip%20Sheet%20-%</a><a href=\"http://www.ncpc.org/topics/cyberbullying/cyberbullying-tip-sheets/NCPC%20Tip%20Sheet%20-%20Spotting%20The%20Signs.pdf\">20Spotting%20The%20Signs.pdf</a></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt; color: #000000;\">L0714384024[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Top 5 Warning Signs Your Child is Being Cyberbullied','','inherit','open','open','','907-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 18:02:16','2014-08-12 18:02:16','',907,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/907-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(980,7,'2014-08-12 18:20:23','2014-08-12 18:20:23','<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-933\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/21-Article-Oversharing-Online-Image-3000x1999.jpg\" alt=\"21 - Article - Oversharing Online Image\" width=\"3000\" height=\"1999\" /><em>How Much is Too Much?</em></span></p>\n<p>Its so much easier for our children to connect with friends today. New or old, they are just a click away. With each post, like, check-in or status update, they share a little bit about themselves and their families. Before this bad habit becomes a risk to your entire family, talk to your children about smart and safe behavior online.</p>\n<p><strong>Forever is a long time</strong></p>\n<p>Its fun to be the first to post a crazy photo from a great weekend or a silly video of friends. But before each post, encourage your child to think about the implications. Sometimes these posts can garner unwanted attention. By the time you try to delete them, it may be too late and the damage can linger for years to come.</p>\n<p><strong>Personal means personal</strong></p>\n<p>About half of teens report that they have shared their email addresses online, about one-third has shared phone numbers, and 15 percent say theyve published a home address.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p>If this information ends up in the wrong hands, it could be dangerous. Strangers with access to your home address could commit mail fraud, stage a break-in or even use the information to steal your identity. Children may not see the bigger picture, so talk to them about the risks associated with sharing personal information.</p>\n<p><strong>Privacy is key</strong></p>\n<p>Despite what some may think, what happens on one device doesnt necessarily stay on that device and could end up on the Internet. Sit down with your children and talk about keeping personal photos personal and not to share via text or social media. Its important for children to understand that just because they are practicing safe Internet practices, others may not be and could share photos that you dont want seen by the public. </p>\n<p><strong>Real-time alerts</strong></p>\n<p>Empower your kids and teens to ask questions about what to share online and to talk to you about any issues with their online life. MetLife Defender is here to help you stay educated on issues affecting your kids online.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Learn more </a>about safe Internet practices and options for enrolling in our Family Plan to get alerts on suspected acts of cyberbullying or predation on your childrens Facebook, Twitter or Instagram accounts.</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><sup>1</sup>McAfee. (July, 2014) <em>McAfees 2014 Teens and Screens</em>. Retrieved from <a href=\"http://blogs.mcafee.com/consumer/teens-and-screens\">http://blogs.mcafee.com/consumer/teens-and-screens</a></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384026[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Oversharing Online: TMI!','','inherit','open','open','','931-autosave-v1','','','2014-08-12 18:20:23','2014-08-12 18:20:23','',931,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/931-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(981,7,'2014-08-12 18:20:58','2014-08-12 18:20:58','<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-933\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/21-Article-Oversharing-Online-Image-3000x1999.jpg\" alt=\"21 - Article - Oversharing Online Image\" width=\"3000\" height=\"1999\" /><em>How Much is Too Much?</em></span></p>\r\n<p>Its so much easier for our children to connect with friends today. New or old, they are just a click away. With each post, like, check-in or status update, they share a little bit about themselves and their families. Before this bad habit becomes a risk to your entire family, talk to your children about smart and safe behavior online.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Forever is a long time</strong></p>\r\n<p>Its fun to be the first to post a crazy photo from a great weekend or a silly video of friends. But before each post, encourage your child to think about the implications. Sometimes these posts can garner unwanted attention. By the time you try to delete them, it may be too late and the damage can linger for years to come.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Personal means personal</strong></p>\r\n<p>About half of teens report that they have shared their email addresses online, about one-third has shared phone numbers, and 15 percent say theyve published a home address.<sup>1</sup></p>\r\n<p>If this information ends up in the wrong hands, it could be dangerous. Strangers with access to your home address could commit mail fraud, stage a break-in or even use the information to steal your identity. Children may not see the bigger picture, so talk to them about the risks associated with sharing personal information.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Privacy is key</strong></p>\r\n<p>Despite what some may think, what happens on one device doesnt necessarily stay on that device and could end up on the Internet. Sit down with your children and talk about keeping personal photos personal and not to share via text or social media. Its important for children to understand that just because they are practicing safe Internet practices, others may not be and could share photos that you dont want seen by the public. </p>\r\n<p><strong>Real-time alerts</strong></p>\r\n<p>Empower your kids and teens to ask questions about what to share online and to talk to you about any issues with their online life. MetLife Defender is here to help you stay educated on issues affecting your kids online.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/online-child-safety/923/\">Learn more about safe Internet practices</a> and options for enrolling in our Family Plan to get alerts on suspected acts of cyberbullying or predation on your childrens Facebook, Twitter or Instagram accounts.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><sup>1</sup>McAfee. (July, 2014) <em>McAfees 2014 Teens and Screens</em>. Retrieved from <a href=\"http://blogs.mcafee.com/consumer/teens-and-screens\">http://blogs.mcafee.com/consumer/teens-and-screens</a></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384026[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Oversharing Online: TMI!','','inherit','open','open','','931-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 18:20:58','2014-08-12 18:20:58','',931,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/931-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(982,7,'2014-08-12 18:22:12','2014-08-12 18:22:12','<p><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-920\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/20-Article-Online-Child-Predation-7-8-14-Image-2000x3000.jpg\" alt=\"imsis550-173\" width=\"2000\" height=\"3000\" /><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; font-style: italic;\">Tips for Keeping Your Children Safe Online</span></p>\r\n<p>Never accept a ride from a stranger. Come straight home from school. Dont talk to strangers.</p>\r\n<p>If youre like most parents, youve been having similar conversations with your children since they were old enough to talk. But today, the danger doesnt just look like a suspicious character in a strange car, it exists online. Todays technology makes it easier than ever for strangers to target and contact your children. Get up to speed on the dangers they face and talk to your children about being safe online.</p>\r\n<p><strong>The online stranger</strong></p>\r\n<p>Its simple. Stranger equals no. Its easy for anyone to message your son or daughter about his or her favorite sports team, or even pretend to be a mutual friend of relatives. Remind your child if he or she is contacted by a stranger not to respond to the person in question and tell an adult.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Privacy please!</strong></p>\r\n<p>Privacy nowadays is more than shutting your door or closing the blinds, online privacy is key too! Read the privacy settings on all social media sites and decide with your child exactly how much information is best to share. Educate your child about what could happen if sensitive information is made available to strangers.</p>\r\n<p><strong>A friend of a friends friend doesnt have to be a friend of yours</strong></p>\r\n<p>Online sites are great at suggesting people you might know. Children and teens enjoy having large social networks, which makes it intriguing to accept friend requests from people who are friends with their social groups. It is important to review that just because an individual is a friend or relative of a friend, does not mean it is safe. While it can be fun for your child to connect the dots back from the friend she met at the beach last summer to your second cousins tennis instructors daughter, its an activity best done by you and your child together.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Taking control</strong></p>\r\n<p>Keeping tabs on your childs digital life can be overwhelming, even if you are armed with the best tips. MetLife Defenders Family Plan is a great option to monitor your childs social media accounts when you cant. It consistently scans your childs Facebook, Twitter and Instagram accounts to flag any suspected acts of predation and cyberbullying. <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\"><strong>Learn more about your options here.</strong></a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384029[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','A Lot More Than Child\'s Play','','inherit','open','open','','923-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 18:22:12','2014-08-12 18:22:12','',923,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/923-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(983,7,'2014-08-12 18:23:05','2014-08-12 18:23:05','<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-469\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/14-Article-Good-Habits-Mean-Safety-Long-Term-3000x2000.jpg\" alt=\"14 - Article - Good Habits Mean Safety Long Term\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><em>Tips for Protecting Our Tech-Savvy Kids from Online Identity Theft</em></span></p>\r\n<p>LOL. OMG. TTYS. If you have kids, you probably know what were talking about. And while this innocent cyber language can be fun, its also a clue to how much time our children are spending online and the risks involved with it.</p>\r\n<p>A 2013 poll showed that the average tween and teen spent at least five hours per day online, and 86percentof them believed social networking sites to be safe.<sup>1</sup> Almost all of their parents agreed, but unfortunately, this is not the case.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Easy as A.B.C.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Predators and cybercriminals are going after an easier target these days: our children. Between cell phones, tablets, and laptops, todays children are rarely more than a click away from the digital worldeven while at school. And stealing a childs information is easier than you think.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Who are they talking to?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Our children have the world at their fingertips. That also means that they can communicate with a world full of people. And while they may be gaming, chatting, and sharing with friends, they could also be interacting with complete strangers.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Passwords are only as strong as you make them</strong></p>\r\n<p>We often create passwords that have to do with our personal life, referencing information such as our address, phone number and birth date. Unfortunately, our kids do this too and the abundance of information on the Internet makes it incredibly simple for someone to steal.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Does it really matter? And how much can they find out about my child online?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Absolutely! Aside from your childs safety, his or her identity is also at risk. And for that matter, your identity. Imagine finding out that your daughter has a mortgage (unpaid of course) in a faraway state, or that your son has outstanding hospital bills. It seems impossible, but because we typically dont keep close tabs on what kind of information our children are sharing, identity theft happens. And its no laughing matter. Child identity theft can cause huge problems for them down the road when they want to buy a car or apply for student loans.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Protect yourself and your children from online danger</strong></p>\r\n<p>MetLife Defendercan help by providing constant monitoring, protection, and resources to keep you safe. <strong><a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\">Enroll today</a> and start experiencing better online protection for you and your family.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">1. McAfee. (2013, June). <em>McAfee Digital Deception Study 2013. </em>Retrieved from: http://www.mcafee.com/us/resources/reports/rp-digital-deception-survey.pdf</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0614379029[exp0615][All States][DC]</span></p>','Your Children: Good Habits Now Mean Safety Long-Term','','inherit','open','open','','466-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 18:23:05','2014-08-12 18:23:05','',466,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/466-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
