	(999,7,'2014-08-13 16:20:38','2014-08-13 16:20:38','<p>The statistics are staggering: Hacking and internal corporate fraud are steadily rising. So how do you keep your family safe?</p>\r\n<p>No doubt about it: 2013 was the worst year for identity fraud in U.S. history. More than 500 million personal records were exposed to hackers or thieves leaving 13 million people victims of identity fraud.<sup>1,2</sup></p>\r\n<p>Breaches ranged from credit card number exposures to medical record thefts and, if the first half of 2014 is any indication, these cases will continue to rise. In fact, according to the Identity Theft Resource Center, 368 breaches have occurred this year so far - that\'s up nearly 19 percent from the same period last year!<sup>1</sup></p>\r\n<p><strong>Can this trend be stopped? </strong></p>\r\n<p>While online breaches are becoming more fact than fiction, by taking control of your digital life you can write your own ending to the story.</p>\r\n<p>Practicing the basics can go a long way. Keep your passwords complex and updated, check your online accounts for suspicious behaviors, and stay up-to-date on the latest Internet protection tips at MetLifeDefender.com.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-802\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/19-Infographic-The-Year-of-the-Data-Breach_v4-page-001.jpg\" alt=\"19 - Infographic - The Year of the Data Breach_v4-page-001\" width=\"1744\" height=\"1718\" /></p>','The Year of the Data Breach','','inherit','open','open','','946-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 16:20:38','2014-08-13 16:20:38','',946,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/946-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(1000,7,'2014-08-13 16:20:54','2014-08-13 16:20:54','<p><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-941\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/22-Article-Heartbleed-Image-3000x2250.jpg\" alt=\"22 - Article - Heartbleed Image\" width=\"3000\" height=\"2250\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><em>Protecting Your Privacy on the Web</em></span></p>\r\n<p>Eavesdropping on conversations. Stealing data. Impersonating users. The elements of a great spy novel?</p>\r\n<p>Sure, but in this case, theyre the results of the recent Heartbleed bug which served as an important wake up call for safer Internet behaviors.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Bug in brief</strong></p>\r\n<p>The infamous 2014 Heartbleed bug took the Internet by storm and potentially exposed millions of usernames and passwords on several of todays most popular sites.</p>\r\n<p>Unlike large scale data breaches of the past few years, the Heartbleed bug was a new type of breach which affected a code known as OpenSSL. OpenSSL is widely used across websites to encrypt user-provided information on servers and it is estimated that nearly two-thirds of all Internet sites use the code.</p>\r\n<p><strong>So what?</strong></p>\r\n<p>While all this technical Internet talk may leave you scratching your head, what you really need to know is that your information could still be at risk. A new report shows that as many as 300,000 sites are still vulnerable with many failing to implement the patches now that the initial scare is over.<sup>1 </sup></p>\r\n<p>MetLife Defenders security analysts suggest changing and varying your passwords on the following websites that may have been affected, if you havent already done so:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>DropBox</li>\r\n<li>Facebook</li>\r\n<li>Flickr</li>\r\n<li>Google</li>\r\n<li>Gmail</li>\r\n<li>Instagram</li>\r\n<li>OkCupid</li>\r\n<li>Tumblr</li>\r\n<li>Yahoo</li>\r\n<li>Yahoo Mail</li>\r\n<li>YouTube</li>\r\n<li>Wikipedia</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>While this does not mean that your information was exposed, it\'s always better to be safe than sorry and avoid incidents of identity theft.</p>\r\n<p>If you are worried that your data is vulnerable, <a href=\"https://www.metlifedefender.com/register/plan/?\"><strong>enroll in MetLife Defender</strong></a> to get proactive protection for your financial, medical and personal data online.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><sup>1</sup> Erratta Security (2014) Retrieved from: http://blog.erratasec.com/2014/05/300k-servers-vulnerable-to-heartbleed.html#.U7RxypRdXHW</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714383411[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','Stop the Heartbleeding','','inherit','open','open','','939-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 16:20:54','2014-08-13 16:20:54','',939,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/939-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(1001,7,'2014-08-13 16:22:33','2014-08-13 16:22:33','<p>The statistics are staggering: Hacking and internal corporate fraud are steadily rising. So how do you keep your family safe?</p>\r\n<p>No doubt about it: 2013 was the worst year for identity fraud in U.S. history. More than 500 million personal records were exposed to hackers or thieves leaving 13 million people victims of identity fraud.<sup>1,2</sup></p>\r\n<p>Breaches ranged from credit card number exposures to medical record thefts and, if the first half of 2014 is any indication, these cases will continue to rise. In fact, according to the Identity Theft Resource Center, 368 breaches have occurred this year so far - that\'s up nearly 19 percent from the same period last year!<sup>1</sup></p>\r\n<p><strong>Can this trend be stopped? </strong></p>\r\n<p>While online breaches are becoming more fact than fiction, by taking control of your digital life you can write your own ending to the story.</p>\r\n<p>Practicing the basics can go a long way. Keep your passwords complex and updated, check your online accounts for suspicious behaviors, and stay up-to-date on the latest Internet protection tips at MetLifeDefender.com.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-802\" src=\"https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/19-Infographic-The-Year-of-the-Data-Breach_v4-page-001.jpg\" alt=\"19 - Infographic - The Year of the Data Breach_v4-page-001\" width=\"1744\" height=\"1718\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714384027[exp0715][All States][DC]</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\">L0714383422[exp0715][All States][DC]</span></p>','The Year of the Data Breach','','inherit','open','open','','946-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 16:22:33','2014-08-13 16:22:33','',946,'https://toolsandtips.metlifedefender.com/uncategorized/946-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
